      whenToSeekHelp: 'If dissociation happens more than once, lasts longer than the sit itself, or starts happening outside of practice (in daily life), see a trauma-informed therapist immediately. Persistent dissociation is treatable but requires specialized care. If you have a trauma history, work with a trauma-trained mindfulness teacher rather than learning from apps or generic instruction.',
      normalizingMessage: 'Dissociation during meditation is not a failure of practice and not a sign you are broken; it is your nervous system doing something it learned to do for very good reasons. With the right support, you can learn practices that build safety in the body instead of disconnection from it.',
      research: 'Treleaven D (2018). Trauma-Sensitive Mindfulness. W.W. Norton. Lindahl JR, et al. (2017). PLOS ONE. NCTSN (National Child Traumatic Stress Network) clinical guidelines.'
